[[File:Jesse Owens3.jpg|thumb|right|upright|The award bears [[Jesse Owens]]' name.]] {{about|the annual track and field award|Big Ten Conference Athlete of the Year|Big Ten Athlete of the Year}} The '''Jesse Owens Award''' is an annual [[track and field]] award that is the highest accolade given out by [[USA Track and Field]] (USATF).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usatf.org/statistics/awards/TF/JesseOwensAward.asp |accessdate=November 3, 2010 |title=Jesse Owens Award |publisher=[[USA Track and Field]] |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090304192040/http://www.usatf.org/statistics/awards/TF/JesseOwensAward.asp |archivedate=March 4, 2009 |df= }}</ref> As the country's highest award for the sport, it bears [[Jesse Owens]]' name in recognition of his significant career, which included four gold medals at the [[1936 Summer Olympics|1936 Olympic Games]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.usatf.org/news/view.aspx?duid=USATF_2009_11_19_13_34_17 | title = Gay, Richards win 2009 Jesse Owens Awards| publisher = [[USA Track and Field]] | date = November 19, 2009| accessdate=November 3, 2010}}</ref> First awarded in 1981 to [[hurdles|hurdler]] [[Edwin Moses]], it was created to recognize the season's top [[United States|American]] performer in track and field competitions. In 1996, the award was divided into two categories, with both a male and female winner. The 1996 winners, [[Michael Johnson (athlete)|Michael Johnson]] and [[Gail Devers]], each won two gold medals at that year's [[1996 Summer Olympics|Olympics in Atlanta]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.iaaf.org/news/kind=100/newsid=54927.html |title = Gay, Richards selected USA Athletes of the Year| publisher=[[International Association of Athletics Federations]] | date = November 20, 2009| accessdate=November 3, 2010}}</ref> Up to 2008, the award was voted on by members of the United States athletics media only, but in 2009 fans were able to vote via the USA Track and Field website, with their opinions contributing 10% of the overall result.<ref name=smh/>
The winners of the award are typically announced in late November or early December after the end of the outdoor track and field season. A number of athletes have received the award on more than one occasion: [[Jackie Joyner-Kersee]] was the first to do so with back-to-back wins in 1986 and 1987, while [[Carl Lewis]] won his second award in 1991. [[Michael Johnson (athlete)|Michael Johnson]] was the first to receive the award three times (winning consecutively from 1994–1996) and [[Marion Jones]] became the first woman to collect three awards after wins in 1997, 1998 and 2002. In 2012, [[Allyson Felix]] won the award for the fourth time, thus distinguishing herself as the athlete with the most wins. 2014 winners are [[Mebrahtom Keflezighi]] and [[Jennifer Simpson]]. Winners receive a replica of the award while the original remains on permanent display at the USATF Headquarters in [[Indianapolis, Indiana]].<ref name=2010award/>
As of 2013, the female version of the award was renamed the '''Jackie Joyner-Kersee Athlete of the Year Award'''.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.usatf.org/statistics/Annual-Awards/TF/JesseOwensAward.aspx | title = Jesse Owens Award| publisher = USA Track & Field | accessdate = October 18, 2017}}</ref> {{clear}}
