{{Infobox venue | name = Nobelhallen | nickname = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | fullname = | former names = | logo_image = | logo_caption = | image = | image_size = | image_alt = | caption = | pushpin_map = | pushpin_mapsize = | pushpin_map_caption = | pushpin_label_position = | address = | location = [[Karlskoga]], [[Sweden]] | coordinates = | type = [[indoor arena]] | genre = | broke_ground = | built = | opened = {{Start date|df=y|1971}} | renovated = | expanded = | closed = | demolished = | owner = | operator = | surface = | scoreboard = | cost = | architect = | project_manager = | structural engineer = | services engineer = | general_contractor = | main_contractors = | seating_type = | capacity = | suites = | record_attendance = | dimensions = | field_shape = | acreage = | volume = | tenants = [[BIK Karlskoga]] | embedded = | website = | publictransit = }} '''Nobelhallen''' is an indoor [[arena]] in [[Karlskoga]], [[Örebro County]], [[Sweden]]. Its current capacity is 5,600<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.karlskoga.se/Uppleva--gora/Gora/Idrott-motion-och-friluftsliv/Nobelstadion-och-Nobelhallen.html |title=Nobelstadion och Nobelhallen - Alfred Nobels Karlskoga |publisher=Karlskoga.se |date=2014-10-06 |accessdate=2015-03-01 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150406071944/http://karlskoga.se/Uppleva--gora/Gora/Idrott-motion-och-friluftsliv/Nobelstadion-och-Nobelhallen.html |archivedate=2015-04-06 |df= }}</ref> and it was built in 1971. It is the home arena of the [[ice hockey]] team [[BIK Karlskoga]].
